\begin_layout Section
Large-
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can take the classical limit by formally sending 
\begin_inset Formula $j\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 such that the spin operators effectively commute, 
\begin_inset Formula $[J_{\alpha},J_{\beta}]=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then each spin operator may be replaced with its expectation value,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{\alpha}\rightarrow\langle J_{\alpha}\rangle=s_{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Correspondly, one should replace 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\rightarrow S^{2}=s_{x}^{2}+s_{y}^{2}+s_{z}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The large 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 limit implies that each Stevens operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 becomes a homogeneous polynomial of order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

; all terms not at leading order should be ignored.
 As a classical function, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}(\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the spherical harmonic 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{l,m}(\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\rightarrow m$
\end_inset

, and the normalized vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 is replaced by its polar coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 The constant of proportionality varies as a function of both 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a shorthand, define 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\equiv(s_{x},s_{y})$
\end_inset

.
 To evaluate gradients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}(\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

, first note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx} & =\frac{d}{ds_{+}}+\frac{d}{ds_{-}}\label{eq:d_dx}\\
-i\frac{d}{dy} & =\frac{d}{ds_{+}}-\frac{d}{ds_{-}},\label{eq:d_dy}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the derivatives on the right are Wirtinger derivatives, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\pm}=x\pm iy=(s_{\mp})^{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
 For a real function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s_{+},s_{-})$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{df}{ds_{-}}=\left(\frac{df}{ds_{+}}\right)^{\ast},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{df}{dx} & =\frac{df}{ds_{+}}+\left(\frac{df}{ds_{-}}\right)^{\ast}=2\mathrm{Re}\frac{df}{ds_{+}}\\
\frac{df}{dy} & =-\frac{1}{i}\left(\frac{df}{ds_{+}}-\left(\frac{df}{ds_{+}}\right)^{\ast}\right)=-2\mathrm{Im}\frac{df}{ds_{+}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The classical Stevens functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}(\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

 involve 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{+}^{n}\pm s_{-}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 An important identity is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f_{1} & =\frac{s_{+}^{n}+s_{-}^{n}}{2}=\mathrm{Re}s_{+}^{n}\implies\frac{df_{1}}{ds_{+}}=\frac{n}{2}s_{+}^{n-1}\\
f_{2} & =\frac{s_{+}^{n}-s_{-}^{n}}{2i}=\mathrm{Im}s_{+}^{n}\implies\frac{df_{2}}{ds_{+}}=\frac{n}{2i}s_{+}^{n-1}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

These results can be used in combination with Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:d_dx"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:d_dy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to get the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}(\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

 with respect to both 
\begin_inset Formula $x=s_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=s_{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Application to linear spin wave theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a spin-
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 quantum Hamiltonian.
 The single-ion anisotropy may be modeled as an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 acting on the local spin Hilbert space, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2S+1$
\end_inset

.
 It is always possible to decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 as linear combination of Stevens operators, each of which is a polynomial
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 spin operators 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, as defined above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In LSWT it is convenient to locally rotate the reference frame so that the
 ground state magnetic ordering is aligned with the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-direction.
 This rotation corresponds to a unitary transformation on local quantum
 operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\Lambda}=U^{\dagger}\Lambda U,\quad\tilde{\mathbf{J}}=U^{\dagger}\mathbf{J}U.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The rotated single-ion anisotropy operator can be expanded in Stevens operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\Lambda}=\sum_{k,q}\tilde{c}_{k,q}\mathcal{O}_{k,q},\label{eq:Lambda_tilde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

involving new coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce Holstein-Primakoff bosons 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b,b^{\dagger}\}$
\end_inset

 to represent the spin operators.
 Condense in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-direction, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $J^{z}$
\end_inset

 (in the rotated frame) becomes a number operator, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{z}=S-b^{\dagger}b,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\pm}=J_{x}\pm iJ_{y}$
\end_inset

 are approximated as bosonic annihilation/creation operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{+}\approx\sqrt{2S}\,b,\quad J_{-}\approx\sqrt{2S}\,b^{\dagger}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hamiltonian may be expanded in powers of bosons.
 At zeroth order, one obtains the ground state classical energy.
 Terms at linear order cancel because the gradient of the classical energy
 at the ground state is zero.
 Terms quadratic in the bosons describe a leading order approximation to
 magnon excitations, which becomes exact in the large-
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our purpose is to extract these quadratic terms for the rotated anisotropy
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 contains a prefactor 
\begin_inset Formula $(J_{+}^{q}\pm J_{-}^{q})$
\end_inset

, which itself is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in the bosons.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|\geq3$
\end_inset

 cannot contribute to the Hamiltonian at quadratic order.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|=1$
\end_inset

 consists entirely of terms that are odd in bosons.
 This leaves only terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\{0,\pm2\}$
\end_inset

 that can contribute to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 at quadratic order in bosons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the large-
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 limit, Stevens operators become homogeneous polynomials at highest order
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 These are, for 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{2,0} & =3J_{z}^{2}-S^{2}\\
\mathcal{O}_{4,0} & =35J_{z}^{4}-30S^{2}J_{z}^{2}+3S^{4}\\
\mathcal{O}_{6,0} & =231J_{z}^{6}-315S^{2}J_{z}^{4}+105S^{4}J_{z}^{2}-5S^{6},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and for 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\pm2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{2,\pm2} & =\phi_{\pm}(J_{+}^{2}\pm J_{-}^{2})+\hc\\
\mathcal{O}_{4,\pm2} & =\phi_{\pm}(J_{+}^{2}\pm J_{-}^{2})(7J_{z}^{2}-S^{2})+\hc\\
\mathcal{O}_{6,\pm2} & =\phi_{\pm}(J_{+}^{2}\pm J_{-}^{2})(33J_{z}^{4}-18S^{2}J_{z}^{2}+S^{4})+\hc
\end{align*}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

, the quadratic boson terms are obtained by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{z}^{n}\rightarrow-nS^{n-1}b^{\dagger}b,
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\pm2$
\end_inset

, the quadratic boson terms are obtained by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
J_{z} & \rightarrow S,\\
J_{+}^{2}\pm J_{-}^{2} & \rightarrow2S(bb\pm b^{\dagger}b^{\dagger}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

After substitution and simplification, one finds the replacement rules,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{O}_{k,0} & \rightarrow-a_{0}^{(k)}S^{k-1}b^{\dagger}b,\\
\mathcal{O}_{k,\pm2} & \rightarrow\phi_{\pm}a_{2}^{(k)}S^{k-1}(bb\pm b^{\dagger}b^{\dagger}),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{0}^{(2)} & =6,\,a_{0}^{(4)}=80,\,a_{0}^{(6)}=336.\\
a_{2}^{(2)} & =4,\,a_{2}^{(4)}=24,\,a_{2}^{(6)}=64,
\end{align}

\end_inset

and scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 are defined in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:phi_def"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 These rules may be used in the context of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 expansion given in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Lambda_tilde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
